Ex hirco lavem nunquam mutabis Echinum.

                  FRogs are divided, by Phyſitians, into ſeveral kinds; ſome tell us that there are none in the Sea, but only in gardens, and in the fields; ſometimes in Ponds and Lakes: thoſe that are more venomous, are called Toads, and are to be found only in holes; which, like the Bat, never come out of their holes but in the night-time. 1. Our common Frogs, by their continual croaking, do very much trouble and infeſt us; which Ovid telleth us of, in his Metam. concerning the Countrey-men that were changed into Frogs.


Quanquam ſunt ſub aqua, ſub aqua maledicere gaudent;

Litibus exercent linguas pulſoque pudore.



Their brawling tongues, but ſetting ſhame aſide;

Though hid in water, under water chide.
